    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-02-04T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-02-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="17"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d17">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.5/2–252</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_FRANKSSOS1" type="to">Franks</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d17fn1">This letter was drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_BYROADEHA1">Byroade</persName> and was cleared by <persName
                            corresp="#p_PERKINSGW1">Perkins</persName> (<gloss target="#t_EUR1"
                            >EUR</gloss>) and <persName corresp="#p_KNIGHTRB1">Knight</persName>
                            (<gloss target="#t_SA1">S/A</gloss>). It was delivered to the British
                        Embassy on Feb. 4, apparently by <persName corresp="#p_CALHOUNJA1"
                            >Calhoun</persName> (<gloss target="#t_GER1">GER</gloss>).</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-02-04">February 4,
                            1952</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Ambassador</hi>: I should appreciate your
                    transmitting the following personal message to Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_EDENSA1">Eden</persName>, in reply to his message to me of
                    February 2 delivered to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BYROADEHA1">Byroade</persName>
                    by Mr. <persName corresp="#p_PORTERIF1">Ivor Porter</persName> on Saturday
                        evening:<note n="2" xml:id="d17fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_17">p. 17</ref>.</note>
                    <pb facs="0069" n="25" xml:id="pg_25"/>
                    <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Thank you for your message of February 2. I am delighted that it was
                            possible for you to be in Paris at this particular time and am certain
                            that your talks there will prove to be helpful to all of us.</p>
                        <p>“I assume that by now you will have seen a copy of my reply to M.
                                <persName corresp="#p_SCHUMANR1">Schuman</persName>’s recent
                                letter,<note n="3" xml:id="d17fn3">Dated Jan. 29, <ref
                                    target="#pg_7">p. 7</ref>.</note> of which he sent you a copy,
                            and are therefore aware of my views on the substantive questions he
                            raised. I shall be glad to leave the specific question of inviting
                            Chancellor <persName corresp="#p_ADENAUERK1">Adenauer</persName> to meet
                            with us in London next week entirely in your hands. I think we must
                            assume at this stage that a meeting of minds on the major German
                            questions can be achieved between the three of us, and with <persName
                                corresp="#p_ADENAUERK1">Adenauer</persName>. If the Lisbon meeting
                            is to be productive of accomplishments on matters vital to the forward
                            progress of our defensive efforts, agreement must be reached on these
                            issues. It is my hope therefore that it will be possible to have the
                            Chancellor join us, but I agree that the matter need not be settled for
                            a few days. I gave these views to Ambassador <persName
                                corresp="#p_BONNETH1">Bonnet</persName>, who called on me Saturday
                            at M. <persName corresp="#p_SCHUMANR1">Schuman</persName>’s request to
                            discuss this same question.”<note n="4" xml:id="d17fn4">For <persName
                                    corresp="#p_ACHESONDG1">Acheson</persName>’s memorandum of his
                                conversation with <persName corresp="#p_BONNETH1">Bonnet</persName>
                                on Feb. 2, see <ref target="#pg_17">p. 17</ref>.</note>
                        </p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>[<signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_ACHESONDG1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dean Acheson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>]</closer>
            </div>
